Assignment #1 -- Data Preprocessing and Visualization¶

Questions to Address:

  1. Calculate the average SRT of every 10 minutes, and plot the SRT with a line chart (x axis for date time and y axis for the average SRT).
  2. Calculate the average of each SRT component of every 10 minute, and plot the four SRT components together with a stacked area chart (x axis for date time and y axis for time) and also a 100% stacked area chart (y axis for the percentage).
  3. Plot the CDF (Cumulative distribution function) chart of SRT.
  4. Plot the CDF chart of #Images.
  5. Count the number of queries (also called page views or PVs) of each minute, and plot the minute-level PVs with a line chart (x axis for date time and y axis for the PVs).
  6. Count the PVs of each province, and plot it with a histogram chart (x axis for province and y axis for PVs).
  7. Count the PVs of each UA, and plot it with a pie chart (show the percentages in the chart).
  8. What are the differences among those charts (How to decide which one to use)
  9. Describe your experience or findings in doing those jobs. For example, experience of processing the data, observations from the charts, characteristics of the data, potential explanations, and any interesting things you would like to mention.

Chart Generations¶

Calculate the average SRT of every 10 minutes, and plot the SRT with a line chart (x axis for date time and y axis for the average SRT).¶

Analysis: From the line chart, we observe that the trend seems to repeat across same-time-different-days. For instance, during the early morning hours, the SRT would be lower. However, the SRT would peak in the mid-day (towards the evening).

Therefore, from the perspective of the search engine, we should consider using a time-series forecasting approach if we want to do prediction for the SRT. However, the changes in these values could be due to a myriad of reasons - e.g. due to the SRT components, or due to other variables. Therefore, we should breakdown the SRT into components and perform further analysis.

Calculate the average of each SRT component of every 10 minute, and plot the four SRT components together with a stacked area chart (x axis for date time and y axis for time) and also a 100% stacked area chart (y axis for the percentage).¶

Analysis: From the stacked area chart, we notice that the overall trend for all the components are similar (e.g. when Tnet increases, the Tserver, Tbrowser and Tother are likely to increase). It appears that there exist a form of correlation between them. Additionally, the trend seems to repeat across same-time-different-days.

Therefore, from the perspective of the search engine, we should consider using a time-series forecasting approach if we want to do prediction for the SRT components. The correlation between each component could also suggest that the SRT values could be correlated to other factors such as number of page views per minute, etc. Therefore, we should perform further analysis subsequently.

From the 100% stacked area chart, we can see from the color that the majority of SRT is due to Tother, followed by Tnet and Tserver.

Thus, from the perspective of the search engine, if we want to reduce the SRT, we should explore what reasons would fall under Tother and fix them. Otherwise, reinspecting our network structure / architecture and our server's CPU and utilisation could be a viable approach.

Plot the CDF (Cumulative distribution function) chart of SRT.¶

Analysis: From the PDF, we can see that the distribution of SRT is ideal, where most are centered around 468.0ms. The long right-tail is normal due to network latency issues.

From the search engine perspective, we would want to achieve 2 goals.

  1. Minimise SRT in general (the centre of distribution)

    This calls for us to improve our overall infrastructure - be it hardware (via cable laying) or architectural (redesigning the network routes and connections)

  2. Reduce the occurences where SRT is extremely long (in the long right-tail)

    This calls for us to redesign our software approaches to handle such cases (e.g. inspecting our network traffic algorithms in nodes)

Plot the CDF chart of #Images.¶

Analysis: From the PDF, we can see that most webpages have 0, around 12, around 25 images embedded. From the CDF, we can visibly see that the 99th percentile covers 46 while the 99.9th percentile covers 67 images.

From the search engine perspective, if we want to optimise our search / query speed, the above statistics come in handy. For example, if our policy is to render 99.9% of all queries in a fix / benchmarked amount of time, we should aim to be able to render 67 images per query. However, if our policy is slightly more lenient, or if we do not have the required infrastructure or capabilities, we can settle for 46 images, which covers 99% of all queries.

Qualitative Analysis¶

What are the differences among those charts (How to decide which one to use)¶

Each of the chart has their purpose and analysis can be derived from them (please refer to the markdown analysis or in-diagram analysis for each chart above). The usage choice of the charts depends largely on the purpose and intent of the report, as well as from whose perspective.

For instance, if the report is meant to be submitted to the search engine company to call for a review of their infrastructure to reduce latency, then the following chart would be important:

  1. Chart 1 and 2 on average SRT and its components

    These illustrate the time-series trend of and weightage of each component. From the charts, Tother would be the 1st aspect that should be looked into, followed by Tnet and Tserver.

  2. Chart 3 PDF and CDF on SRT

    These illustrate the distribution of network latency amongst users and is useful to benchmark the search engine performance (e.g. 99th percentile of all queries are under the ideal SRT)

  3. Chart 4 on CDF of #Images

    This could be useful if we are inspecting deep into the cause of latency and when deciding on the choice of optimisation algorithms. For example, if Algorithm A results in lower latency (e.g. on Tserver) but would have the side effect of being unable to service many embedded images, the chart can be used to determine what is our "Service Level Agreement".

  4. Chart 5 on PVs per minute

    This is important since the PVs per minute could influence both the Tnet (network bandwidth) and Tserver (CPU utilisation). Being able to redesign the infrastructure and algorithms around this would be handy in optimising cost and performance.

  5. Chart 6 on province

    This can be helpful to determine which provinces to improve the infrastructure first. For example, the top 5 provinces of PVs should be improved first to service more users.

  6. Chart 7 on UA

    This is helpful to determine which browser to optimise our search engine on first. For example, the top browser (Chrome) should have priority when we redesign our search engine application.

On the other hand, if the report is meant to be submitted to advertising agencies / companies to maximum advertisement outreach, a different set of chart would be important:

  1. Chart 6 on province

    This is critical to understand which province do most of the traffic / users come from. With this, advertising can be more targetted. For example, clients targetting the top5 provinces in terms of PVs should engage with advertising / marketing deals with the search engine.

  2. Chart 7 on UA

    If the adverising agency wish to launch a Chrome extension to help users automatically look for the cheapest deals or apply a voucher, this pie chart would be able to justify their approach.

Alternative Interpretation:

  • Line chart: A line chart displays data points connected by lines, making it useful for plotting continuous variables over time, such as search response time (SRT) or the number of page views. It can help identify trends and patterns in the data over time, which can be useful for identifying performance issues or measuring the impact of changes made to the search engine.

  • Stacked area chart: A stacked area chart displays the cumulative total of multiple series on top of each other, making it useful for visualizing the contribution of multiple factors to a single variable, such as the four components of SRT. It can help identify which factors are contributing the most to the overall performance of the search engine, which can be useful for prioritizing improvements.

  • 100% stacked area chart: Similar to a stacked area chart, a 100% stacked area chart shows the composition of different categories over time, but it represents the data as a percentage of the whole. This chart is best used when you want to compare the relative proportion of each category over time.

  • CDF chart: A CDF (cumulative distribution function) chart is useful for visualizing the distribution of a continuous variable, such as SRT per number of images. It is useful in identifying the proportion of searches that fall below a certain threshold, which can be useful for setting performance targets and identifying outliers.

  • Histogram chart: A histogram chart is a bar chart that displays the distribution of a variable by grouping the data into intervals or bins. It is useful for visualizing the distribution of discrete variables, such as page views by province. For example, a histogram chart can help identify which provinces are generating the most traffic to the search engine, which can be useful for targeting marketing efforts or identifying opportunities for expansion.

  • Pie chart: A pie chart is a circular chart that shows the proportion of each category in a data set. It is useful for visualizing the relative contribution of discrete variables, such as page views by user agent. For example, a pie chart can help identify which user agents are generating the most traffic to the search engine, which can be useful for optimizing the search engine for different devices or browsers.

Describe your experience or findings in doing those jobs. For example, experience of processing the data, observations from the charts, characteristics of the data, potential explanations, and any interesting things you would like to mention.¶

Data Preprocessing

It was interesting to have specified the dtypes for the columns, as it helped to reduce the memory consumption and subsequently, the processing speed of the data.

However, the float64 and float32 dtypes still baffles me as the raw data was only up to 2 decimal places, but float32 failed to represent the data accurately.

Chart Generation

In generating the charts, I was considering how to better represent the data and my understanding of the charts. Eventually, I did so in a few ways:

  1. Using distinct colours and flushing certain portions of the chart to the background to draw attention to the important components
  2. Adding additional data labels (such as vertical lines and labelling the x-values / x-ticks) to the graph and pie chart
  3. Shading the area to indicate density and "area under curve" concept for the "Service Level Agreement" / percentile analysis
  4. Applying smoothen to some graphs to derive a slightly different analysis and avoid distractions
  5. Placing 2 graphs side-by-side for easier comparison (such as the PDF and CDF)
  6. Markdown text explaining my analysis of the charts
  7. Adding text in the graphs to highlight the conclusions
  8. Exploring different libraries to achieve similar graphical outputs (such as comparing sns.distplot with matplotlib in terms of both visuals and time performance)

Chart Observations

It was interesting to observe that most of the User Agents were that of a Chrome browser. According to news, Google services such as the Chrome browser have not been available to mainland China users since 2014. This is in contrast with the analysis derived from the logs.

On a side note, chart 2 seems to suggest that the SRT components could be correlated. This could be due to the fact that a high network latency suggests that there are many incoming requests, which would also stress the CPU of the servers and cause other side effects. Therefore, both Tnet and Tserver would fluctuate together.

Lastly, some of the requests were not from the 32 provinces in China, as they were labelled "None". This could be due to the use of VPNs or requests originating from outside of China. Therefore, their IP could not be mapped back to any of those in the Chinese provinces.

Alternative Interpretation:

  • Line chart of average SRT over time: From the line chart, it is evident that the average SRT (search response time) over time is cyclical, where each new day follows a similar pattern. The average SRT is lowest during the early morning and gradually increases throughout the day, with a rapid increase to its highest point during the evening. The increase in SRT over the day could be because of increased user traffic or load on the search engines servers as an increased number of people use the search engine during the day as they embark on their various tasks. The spike in SRT during the evening could also be because people tend to use search engines more after work hours during their leisure time in the evening, leading to a higher load on the search engine's servers.
  • Stacked area charts of composition of average SRT over time: In terms of composition of average SRT, it is evident that Tbrowser (the DOM parsing time of the browser) is the smallest % component of SRT, followed by Tserver (the server-side processing time of the query), Tnet the page transmission time over the network) and finally Tother (the remaining time for acquire other embedded elements in the page, such as images).
    • Tbrowser represents the time spent by the user's browser to parse the document object model (DOM) of the search results page, which occurs first in the search process. This component may be the smallest because modern browsers are optimized for rendering web pages quickly, and parsing the DOM is a fast process.
    • Tserver represents the time spent by the server to process the query and retrieve relevant search results, which occurs after the user enters the search query. This component is typically longer than Tbrowser because it involves more complex processes such as ranking search results and filtering irrelevant results.
    • Tnet represents the time spent transmitting the search results page over the network from the server to the user's browser, which occurs after the server has processed the query and retrieved the results. This component is typically longer than Tserver because network transmission times can be affected by factors like network congestion and bandwidth limitations.
    • Tother represents the remaining time spent acquiring other embedded elements on the search results page, such as images or ads. Possible reasons why it may be the largest component of SRT may be due to the large number of embedded elements. Since the spike in SRT (and also Tother) is at night, it might be due to the fact that people at night tend to watch videos / scroll social media feeds that contains a lot of embedded elements.
  • CDF (Cumulative distribution function) chart of SRT: From the chart, SRT increases at an increasing rate till about 1200 ms, then increases at a decreasing rate. The initial increasing rate of the CDF curve indicates that the majority of the queries have a low response time and are completed relatively quickly. Once the response time crosses a certain threshold (in this case, around 1200 ms), the decreasing rate of increase in the CDF curve may be due to the system reaching its processing capacity or the limitations of the network or hardware. Analyzing the CDF chart in this way can help identify performance bottlenecks and prioritize areas for improvement e.g. to optimise the system for the smaller fraction of queries which are taking longer to improve overall performance and user experience.
  • Histogram chart of PVs per province: From the chart, Guangdong has the highest number of PVs (page views / queries), and Xizang the lowest number of PVs. This might be because Guangdong has a very large population and more economically developed, which lead to a higher number of internet users, and therefore, a higher number of PVs. On the other hand, Xizang has a much smaller population and is a relatively underdeveloped province, leading to fewer internet users and a lower number of PVs.
  • Pie chart of PVs per UA (user agent): From the chart, Chrome has the largest PV at 56.96% due to its fast performance and cross-platform availability, making it a popular choice among users.
